WEBVTT

00:08.965 --> 00:11.750
TOMMY: [ON VOICEMAIL]
This is Tommy.
You know what to do.

00:11.750 --> 00:16.103
Tom, look, I know
I screwed up. Just, please,
call me back, okay?

00:16.103 --> 00:18.888
Just give me a chance
to apologize in person.

00:18.888 --> 00:20.455
CAL: He's playing it all...
Please.

00:20.455 --> 00:22.805
...possessive.

00:22.805 --> 00:23.936
Sorry.

00:27.201 --> 00:31.292
For years, it was
"What's mine is yours,"

00:31.292 --> 00:35.339
and then one day, I was using
his money to pay off
my mom's mortgage.

00:36.949 --> 00:39.952
CAL: And Clay
didn't like that.
No.

00:39.952 --> 00:43.086
It was like I'd betrayed him.

00:43.086 --> 00:47.308
I could tell it was gonna
be one of those nights.
So, I went out.

00:47.308 --> 00:48.787
"One of those nights,"
meaning...

00:52.965 --> 00:56.969
The Clay I knew never hurt me.

00:56.969 --> 01:00.625
He was intense when he played,
but he left it on the field.

01:00.625 --> 01:03.193
At home,
he was like a pussycat.

01:03.193 --> 01:06.892
And I thought, if I waited,
the husband I loved
would come back.

01:06.892 --> 01:08.764
So, Clay wasn't
always like this.
[PHONE BUZZING]

01:08.764 --> 01:09.591
No.

01:12.507 --> 01:16.250
Look, I know it's
what they all say,
but something happened.

01:16.250 --> 01:18.687
You've heard of CTE, right?
Yeah, brain disease.

01:18.687 --> 01:20.254
Athletes and vets get it.

01:20.254 --> 01:22.778
You thought Clay had CTE.
The more I read about it,

01:22.778 --> 01:26.303
explosive anger,
memory loss...
It started to sound familiar.

01:26.303 --> 01:28.088
Did his routine change?

01:30.220 --> 01:33.136
Did he do
anything unusual?
No.

01:33.136 --> 01:35.225
Meet new people?
No.

01:35.225 --> 01:37.401
No, in fact, he spent all his
time at the gym.

01:37.401 --> 01:39.882
He was training
like he was 19 again.

01:39.882 --> 01:44.365
Was it possible
he was using steroids?
No. That was not his thing.

01:44.365 --> 01:48.238
I mean, he knew guys
who did it.

01:48.238 --> 01:53.069
I thought about it, though,
because he was so...

01:53.069 --> 01:56.246
I even looked
around the house.

01:56.246 --> 02:00.729
It's just that it came on
so fast. And one day,
he yelled at me.

02:00.729 --> 02:03.123
The next, he threw a chair
across the room.
Hmm.

02:04.559 --> 02:06.213
It doesn't happen
like that, right?

02:08.215 --> 02:11.522
People don't just wake up one
day, and become a monster.

02:31.629 --> 02:32.804
[BEEPING]

02:32.804 --> 02:34.023
[DOOR BUZZING OPEN]

02:52.563 --> 02:54.565
During our investigation,
we talked to your parents.

02:57.133 --> 02:57.960
They're good people.

03:03.705 --> 03:05.837
Your co-workers all say
you were doing well.

03:09.319 --> 03:11.234
Does that surprise you?

03:12.453 --> 03:13.758
I don't understand.

03:15.717 --> 03:17.153
Given your frame of mind
up to a couple of...

03:17.153 --> 03:19.547
I could use a sandwich.

03:19.547 --> 03:20.765
I was asking...
Good.

03:20.765 --> 03:21.592
Uh...

03:23.203 --> 03:25.640
Tuna, or, um...

03:27.511 --> 03:28.512
Grilled cheese.

03:37.956 --> 03:39.131
Tell me, Tyler,

03:41.308 --> 03:42.613
what changed?

03:43.571 --> 03:45.486
Nothing.

03:45.486 --> 03:49.620
I don't believe that.
Something must have happened.

03:49.620 --> 03:52.188
You would think.

03:52.188 --> 03:53.537
You're just a kid, Tyler.

03:56.888 --> 03:59.543
You had your whole life
ahead of you.

03:59.543 --> 04:00.762
When I was...

04:00.762 --> 04:03.112
Oh, don't try to connect
with me. It's a mistake.

04:07.159 --> 04:10.293
Did you have anything else
planned? Any accomplices?

04:12.600 --> 04:15.994
Why? Wasn't this
spectacle enough?

04:23.350 --> 04:24.176
Is that it?

04:26.048 --> 04:27.397
[SIGHS] Yeah.

04:47.722 --> 04:48.723
Hundred and twenty people.

04:53.684 --> 04:54.685
It filled me up.

05:01.213 --> 05:05.957
Let me go.
I'll give you an encore.

05:22.452 --> 05:23.584
[BEEPING]

05:23.584 --> 05:24.672
[DOOR BUZZING OPEN]

05:25.977 --> 05:26.848
[DOOR CLOSES]

05:52.961 --> 05:56.094
Hey. What's going on
with you?

05:57.966 --> 06:00.403
I talked to the morgue.

06:00.403 --> 06:04.146
They checked opioid ODs
in the last three years,

06:04.146 --> 06:06.017
and they started red-flagging
new ones,

06:06.017 --> 06:08.237
trying to cross-reference
the killer's MO.

06:08.237 --> 06:09.064
And?

06:11.458 --> 06:14.112
And, nothing.
Tally stands at five.

06:14.112 --> 06:16.245
Okay.
For now.

06:16.245 --> 06:19.335
So, Petra says Clay Bishop
didn't do anything unusual,

06:19.335 --> 06:21.250
meet anyone new.
That she knows of.

06:21.250 --> 06:26.037
But his behavior's changing.
Yeah. She thinks this is CTE.

06:26.037 --> 06:28.170
What did the morgue
say about the rash?

06:28.170 --> 06:32.304
It's not caused by fentanyl.
Tox screen doesn't show
any antibodies.

06:32.304 --> 06:34.045
Okay.

06:34.045 --> 06:36.352
What about the pit bull?
How long's Forensics
gonna take?

06:36.352 --> 06:39.790
They're backed up.
DNA's gonna take
at least a day.

06:39.790 --> 06:42.750
If the blood came
from a soldier,
it'll be in the database.

06:42.750 --> 06:45.230
While we're waiting,
let's double back
on the Ramos case.

06:45.230 --> 06:47.885
We should go
and talk to the cop
he fought with.

06:51.759 --> 06:54.762
MAN: [OVER PA]
Blue Team to ICU, please.
Blue Team, ICU.

06:54.762 --> 06:56.807
Tell me
that's not lunch.

06:56.807 --> 07:00.898
Uh, no. It's not lunch.
It's breakfast.

07:00.898 --> 07:03.858
Well, unless you got
your heart set on
Flamin' Hot Cheetos,

07:03.858 --> 07:05.947
I have more than enough.

07:05.947 --> 07:08.123
Oh, yeah, if you're sure.
Yeah.

07:08.123 --> 07:10.081
Great.
Of course.

07:12.519 --> 07:17.437
I got salad, pasta...

07:17.437 --> 07:18.786
Oh, wow,
that looks good.

07:18.786 --> 07:22.790
You doing okay?
Uh, yeah. Good. Thank you.

07:25.793 --> 07:29.840
I mean, I'm busy.
I just need to keep
my head down, you know?

07:29.840 --> 07:31.451
Get people where
they need to be.

07:31.451 --> 07:34.236
It's important work.
Don't discredit what you do.

07:36.238 --> 07:37.326
May I?

07:37.326 --> 07:38.327
Yeah.

07:40.242 --> 07:41.199
Mmm-hmm.

07:43.288 --> 07:44.159
Mmm.

07:45.552 --> 07:46.727
Wow. That is good.

07:47.554 --> 07:48.946
Thank you.

07:56.040 --> 08:00.567
The other night, I, uh...
I just want to thank you

08:01.655 --> 08:03.831
for coming to meet me.

08:03.831 --> 08:06.529
I was testing myself,

08:06.529 --> 08:10.577
and, um, I got through it.
I know.

08:12.317 --> 08:13.493
I believe in you.

08:15.495 --> 08:18.280
I'm here
if you want to talk.

08:20.021 --> 08:21.370
Works both ways.

08:23.633 --> 08:24.808
[POLICE RADIO STATIC]

08:28.464 --> 08:30.510
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

08:37.821 --> 08:39.562
Hey. What...

08:40.955 --> 08:43.653
Officer Connolly,

08:43.653 --> 08:46.874
we'd like to ask you
a few questions
about a traffic stop.

08:46.874 --> 08:49.833
Congressman Eli Ramos.
It happened
a couple of weeks back.

08:49.833 --> 08:51.531
I don't know
what you're talking about.

08:51.531 --> 08:54.925
Officer, this is part
of an ongoing
homicide investigation.

08:54.925 --> 08:57.798
Yeah, I make dozens
of traffic stops a week.

08:59.887 --> 09:03.368
I'm six months out
from my pension. I'm not
looking for any trouble.

09:03.368 --> 09:06.763
We're not looking
to give you any.
You can trust us.

09:10.027 --> 09:14.728
Okay. But I'm not going
on the record
with any of this.

09:14.728 --> 09:18.558
It was made very clear to me
by the brass that this
incident needed to go away.

09:18.558 --> 09:20.821
Fine.

09:20.821 --> 09:26.348
I, uh, pulled Mr. Ramos over
for reckless driving.
He was racing another car.

09:26.348 --> 09:28.263
I figured he might
have had a couple too many,

09:28.263 --> 09:31.048
but, uh, he passed
the breathalyzer
with flying colors.

09:31.048 --> 09:33.660
Okay, was there
any drug use?
No.

09:33.660 --> 09:37.794
No, he was completely lucid,
up until he got in my face.

09:37.794 --> 09:39.448
I said I was letting him off
with a warning,

09:39.448 --> 09:42.625
but, uh,
he flew off the handle,
and took a swing anyway.

09:42.625 --> 09:43.844
Is that where you
got the, uh...

09:46.977 --> 09:48.936
I told my wife
I fell off my bike.

09:50.111 --> 09:51.982
Why did he snap?

09:51.982 --> 09:54.637
In this business,
you see a lot
of people go bananas,

09:54.637 --> 09:57.379
but this, uh,
this was different.

09:57.379 --> 09:59.990
He seemed like a decent guy.
Came out of nowhere.

10:03.559 --> 10:05.517
Okay. Thank you.

10:15.702 --> 10:18.574
FLYNN: Go on. You can go.

10:18.574 --> 10:21.098
Maybe we should let
someone else have a turn.

10:21.098 --> 10:24.493
There's no one here.
Just go.
All right.

10:26.843 --> 10:28.453
FLYNN: Come on,
time's running out.

10:28.453 --> 10:30.107
Try and beat my score.
Just go.

10:30.107 --> 10:32.109
Ugh. Damn it.

10:32.109 --> 10:34.721
We could stop by
the bookstore,

10:34.721 --> 10:37.288
pick up one
of those comics
your mom hates.

10:37.288 --> 10:39.769
We'll talk about that after.
Just try and beat my score.

10:53.609 --> 10:55.524
PAUL: [ECHOING]
Help! Please!

10:57.657 --> 11:00.137
Get help! Get help!

11:07.536 --> 11:11.018
Somebody help! OPERATOR: 911.
What's your emergency?

11:11.018 --> 11:12.933
My grandpa's
having a heart attack.

11:12.933 --> 11:15.762
Where are you located?
We're in North Mall.

11:15.762 --> 11:18.634
Where in North Mall, sir?
The arcade.

11:18.634 --> 11:20.854
We'll dispatch a unit
right away, sir.

11:57.455 --> 11:59.544
[STEADY BEEPING]

12:01.677 --> 12:03.505
[INDISTINCT
ANNOUNCEMENT ON PA]

12:25.614 --> 12:27.398
I was waiting for you.

12:30.532 --> 12:31.794
Dad.

12:37.278 --> 12:40.150
Let me wipe away
the worry.

12:40.150 --> 12:44.676
You're tougher than you think.
Just remember that.

12:44.676 --> 12:46.330
No matter
what happens.

12:51.814 --> 12:54.730
Oh, hey. Hey, Pop.

12:56.210 --> 12:57.951
Is he okay?

12:57.951 --> 13:00.954
Yeah. Yeah, he's fine.
It was just a minor
cardiac event.

13:00.954 --> 13:04.000
It's not a heart attack.
He's stable.
Blood pressure's fine.

13:04.000 --> 13:07.743
They say
I can go home tomorrow,
so, it can't be bad.

13:07.743 --> 13:10.528
About time.
I can't take
the damn hovering.

13:10.528 --> 13:11.791
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

13:12.704 --> 13:14.750
Where's Flynn?

13:14.750 --> 13:17.579
Uh, he's outside. With Nick.

13:17.579 --> 13:21.801
Kid's a hero. If he wasn't
there to help, I don't know
what would have happened.

13:24.325 --> 13:26.109
I'd better go check on him,
okay? I'll be right back.

13:33.464 --> 13:35.336
It's okay, buddy.

13:46.738 --> 13:47.827
Hey.

13:55.922 --> 13:57.837
Come on. What's going on?

13:59.403 --> 14:02.972
It was a game for kids.

14:02.972 --> 14:05.018
He got too excited.
It's not for old people.

14:08.760 --> 14:11.633
But this was all my fault.

14:11.633 --> 14:14.766
Oh, Flynn, no.

14:14.766 --> 14:16.203
No.

14:16.203 --> 14:18.335
I just stood there.
I didn't do anything.

14:18.335 --> 14:22.035
No, you didn't.
You called 911.

14:23.253 --> 14:24.994
You probably
saved his life.

14:24.994 --> 14:26.387
Really?
BOTH: Yeah.

14:28.868 --> 14:32.132
We're really
proud of you, buddy.

14:32.132 --> 14:34.134
We are.
Cool.

15:00.377 --> 15:04.512
Hey.
Hey. I didn't hear
you come in.

15:04.512 --> 15:06.427
Looking good, Dad.

15:06.427 --> 15:10.170
Bullshit. Look like
a mile of rough road.
Still sexy, though.

15:10.170 --> 15:13.738
[LAUGHS] Yeah, you are.

15:24.140 --> 15:25.620
Hey.

15:25.620 --> 15:27.404
Hey.
Hey, it's ready.

15:27.404 --> 15:29.189
Um...
Oh, hey, Em.

15:29.189 --> 15:31.495
Uh, you guys need
any help in here?

15:31.495 --> 15:35.151
Uh, no. We're good.
Jack volunteered
as sous chef.

15:35.151 --> 15:36.936
Really?
JACK: Yeah.

15:36.936 --> 15:38.459
A boy named Sous Chef.

15:38.459 --> 15:40.635
[BOTH LAUGHING]

15:40.635 --> 15:42.158
JACK: Do I put more
of this on as well?
I just put some...

15:42.158 --> 15:43.551
No, no. That's...
You sure?

15:43.551 --> 15:45.161
Yeah, yeah.
Okay. Then it is done.

15:45.161 --> 15:46.728
Great.

15:46.728 --> 15:49.426
Is it good?
Yeah. It's delicious. Thanks.

15:49.426 --> 15:51.124
Would you? Jack. Jack.

15:51.124 --> 15:53.387
I got to have something
to wash this spinach
out of my mouth.

15:53.387 --> 15:54.779
What is with the spinach?

15:54.779 --> 15:57.043
JACK: So, Nick, do you think
they got a chance?

15:57.043 --> 15:59.567
NICK: I dunno. I think this is
their shot at the Cup
this year.

15:59.567 --> 16:01.221
It feels like this is...
I don't know.

16:01.221 --> 16:02.962
They changed the whole
defensive line.

16:02.962 --> 16:04.615
Everything okay?
Thanks. Yeah, everything's...

16:04.615 --> 16:05.486
[PAUL TAPS GLASS]

16:08.358 --> 16:13.189
What happened to me
was a reminder that
I won't always be around.

16:13.189 --> 16:15.061
JACK: Dad.

16:15.061 --> 16:20.414
But I'm glad to spend
the time I have
with my beautiful family.

16:20.414 --> 16:21.502
Slainte.
Slainte,Dad.

16:21.502 --> 16:23.156
Cheers.
Cheers.

16:23.156 --> 16:25.854
Cheers. It's water, but I...
Cheers.

16:25.854 --> 16:28.465
Everyone just needs
to save room for pie.

16:28.465 --> 16:32.817
Helen Byrne's secret recipe.
That's all I'm saying.

16:32.817 --> 16:34.689
JACK: That's the thing
with spinach.
I'm glad you're enjoying it.

16:34.689 --> 16:38.171
Grandpa, are you supposed
to be eating that?

16:38.171 --> 16:41.478
It's fine
for one meal, seriously.

16:41.478 --> 16:43.219
Doctors put you
on a special diet.

16:44.960 --> 16:47.006
All I'm thinking of now,

16:47.006 --> 16:50.618
is this slice of rare beef
and Yorkshire pudding.

16:50.618 --> 16:54.100
We can figure out
the rest in the morning.

16:54.100 --> 16:55.753
If you wake up
in the morning.

16:55.753 --> 16:58.060
Whoa, buddy.
What do you mean?

16:58.060 --> 17:00.149
Look what you're doing
to yourself. You could die.

17:01.368 --> 17:03.544
Flynn.

17:03.544 --> 17:05.546
This family doesn't even know
how to protect each other.

17:05.546 --> 17:07.113
Look at you and Mom!

17:07.113 --> 17:08.897
What the hell is wrong
with you guys?
Flynn, language.

17:08.897 --> 17:10.942
Hey, man, what's going on?
People die!

17:10.942 --> 17:13.597
Valerie died on the train
after you sent her away.

17:15.556 --> 17:16.731
NICK: Flynn.

17:16.731 --> 17:21.040
Who's Valerie?
Sweetie, who died?

17:22.519 --> 17:24.086
Uh, Valerie is Valerie McNair.

17:25.783 --> 17:27.437
She's my biological mom,

17:27.437 --> 17:30.614
and Flynn met her
the other day,
at my apartment.

17:30.614 --> 17:32.181
I goddamn told you.

17:32.181 --> 17:34.227
If you wanted Flynn
to meet her, Emily,

17:34.227 --> 17:36.707
we should have discussed this,
all three of us.

17:36.707 --> 17:40.929
It was an accident.
I didn't... [STAMMERS]
It wasn't supposed to happen.

17:40.929 --> 17:42.104
And that makes it all okay?

17:45.281 --> 17:47.283
This beef
is really delicious, Alice.

17:47.283 --> 17:50.199
You introduced our son,
who is in counseling
for trauma,

17:50.199 --> 17:51.896
to a woman who died,

17:51.896 --> 17:54.421
and then you kept it from us.
Was that an accident, too?

17:54.421 --> 17:56.771
It's not her fault, okay?
Lower your voice, Flynn.

17:56.771 --> 18:01.036
No. It's... I'm...
It's okay. I'm sorry.
I should have told you.

18:01.036 --> 18:05.214
So, why didn't you?
Don't take it personal, Alice.

18:05.214 --> 18:08.696
Emily's always kept her own
counsel, whether she's right
or wrong.

18:08.696 --> 18:11.046
The rest of us
just have to live
with her choices.

18:11.046 --> 18:11.873
Dad.

18:21.361 --> 18:22.884
[CUTLERY AND
CROCKERY CLATTERING]

18:24.581 --> 18:26.540
NICK: No, Em, don't.
[SIGHS]

18:34.591 --> 18:35.375
[DOOR CLOSES]

18:38.639 --> 18:39.683
Emily.

18:43.948 --> 18:45.559
I can't go back in there.

18:47.343 --> 18:48.649
What the hell
were you thinking,

18:48.649 --> 18:50.955
heading the investigation
of your mother's murder?

18:50.955 --> 18:54.089
You think you could just
keep that from the Bureau?

18:54.089 --> 18:57.832
Look, I have
my reasons for it.
You didn't even know her.

18:57.832 --> 18:59.964
There's something in this case
that connects to me,

18:59.964 --> 19:03.620
and I need to figure out
what it is.

19:03.620 --> 19:06.188
You're not gonna get far
freezing out everyone
who can help.

19:11.759 --> 19:13.674
You know I have an obligation
to report this.

19:15.545 --> 19:17.025
So what's stopping you, Nick?

19:32.258 --> 19:34.260
[MUSIC PLAYING ON EARPHONES]

19:40.788 --> 19:43.182
Jesus. Jesus.

19:45.140 --> 19:47.664
Byrne.

19:47.664 --> 19:50.232
I'm gonna
put a bell on you.

19:50.232 --> 19:51.886
I'm here waiting
on the DNA match

19:51.886 --> 19:53.235
from that dog bite.
What are you doing here?

19:54.410 --> 19:57.065
[SIGHS]
Family dinner.

19:57.065 --> 19:59.241
Yeah? Rough night?

20:00.503 --> 20:02.070
Loud. Short.

20:03.767 --> 20:05.465
I've had a few of those.

20:05.465 --> 20:06.944
[SCOFFS]

20:06.944 --> 20:08.337
Yeah, I doubt that.

20:08.337 --> 20:09.773
When your old man
comes home,

20:09.773 --> 20:12.254
and lights into
whichever son
is the nearest,

20:12.254 --> 20:14.691
you learn to give
as good as you get.

20:17.172 --> 20:19.522
I'm sorry.
Don't be.

20:22.351 --> 20:26.094
Me and my brothers inherited
the Isaac mean streak.

20:26.094 --> 20:28.009
I just learned to do
something useful with mine.

20:28.009 --> 20:29.880
OFFICER CONNOLLY:
He flew off the handle
and took a swing, anyway.

20:29.880 --> 20:33.580
He was completely lucid,
up until he got in my face.

20:33.580 --> 20:35.582
[SCREAMING]

20:35.582 --> 20:36.713
PETRA: The Clay I knew
never hurt me.

20:36.713 --> 20:38.411
OFFICER CONNOLLY:
Came out of nowhere.

20:38.411 --> 20:39.977
I told my wife
I fell off my bike.

20:39.977 --> 20:42.066
PETRA:I know
it's what they all say,
but something happened.

20:42.066 --> 20:43.198
Hey. Byrne.

20:43.198 --> 20:44.460
[SNAPS FINGERS]
You with me?

20:46.114 --> 20:47.811
What if he was watching them?

20:50.727 --> 20:52.686
Not just watching them.

20:52.686 --> 20:55.558
What if he was choosing them,
based on their
changed behavior?

20:55.558 --> 20:58.344
Ramos tried to beat up
on a trooper.

20:58.344 --> 21:00.041
Bishop laid into his wife.

21:00.041 --> 21:02.261
Marcos tried to start
a turf war.

21:02.261 --> 21:05.133
Okay. How did he know
to choose them?

21:05.133 --> 21:06.613
Everything happened
behind closed doors.

21:09.442 --> 21:11.357
I don't know.

21:11.357 --> 21:15.361
Okay. Let's just say
he did choose them
because of their behavior.

21:18.451 --> 21:19.452
Why use fentanyl?

21:20.931 --> 21:22.585
It was symbolic.

21:24.761 --> 21:27.068
They were out of control,
and he wanted
to anesthetize them.

21:30.811 --> 21:31.899
Okay.

21:35.772 --> 21:39.385
Then, why? Why them?
How did he find them?

21:39.385 --> 21:41.517
They don't have
schedules that
match up.

21:41.517 --> 21:43.737
We can't find
a common location,

21:43.737 --> 21:45.826
a common person
in their lives.

21:47.871 --> 21:49.786
As far as we can tell,

21:49.786 --> 21:51.310
the only thing these five
people have in common
is the killer.

21:56.619 --> 21:58.839
CROWN: We're five out
from transporting
Tyler Brandon Mills

21:58.839 --> 22:00.841
to the US District Court.

22:00.841 --> 22:05.324
Every precaution has been
taken to manage civilian
and media interference.

22:05.324 --> 22:10.024
To that end, the convoy
will be taking a five-mile
route to the courthouse,

22:10.024 --> 22:13.549
with decoy vehicles
taking alternates. Durand.

22:13.549 --> 22:17.640
You've been divided
into groups of four and
assigned a control vehicle.

22:17.640 --> 22:20.600
Agent Stevens will be manning
the scout vehicle.

22:20.600 --> 22:23.080
Crown will take lead.
I'll take the trail vehicle.

22:23.080 --> 22:26.257
As we move, keep track
of the vehicle in front of you

22:26.257 --> 22:28.477
and remain in radio contact.

22:28.477 --> 22:31.132
Okay, Mills is on his way up
from holding. Let's do this.

22:31.132 --> 22:33.352
Here we go.
Let's take him down.

22:36.311 --> 22:38.313
[CLANGING]

23:17.047 --> 23:17.961
Let's go.

23:28.929 --> 23:30.670
CAL:Holy shit,
we got a match.

23:30.670 --> 23:32.715
Wake up, Byrne. It's in.

23:34.282 --> 23:36.371
I hope you're more
awake than you look.

23:36.371 --> 23:39.287
We've got a DNA match
from that bloody pit bull.

23:39.287 --> 23:40.506
Who is it?

23:40.506 --> 23:42.595
Rex Wolfe.
Look. 6'4", 220.

23:44.727 --> 23:48.731
He's in Special Ops.
At least, he used to be.
75th Army Ranger.

23:48.731 --> 23:50.385
Stationed in Fort Bevans.

23:50.385 --> 23:52.779
Skilled perpetrator.
Clean-cut.
That fits the profile.

23:52.779 --> 23:56.609
Jesus, he's won a lot
of medals. Look, Medal
of Valor, Silver Star.

23:56.609 --> 23:59.699
Then he was discharged,
he hooked up with a PMC.

23:59.699 --> 24:03.833
Tydeus Tech.
So, how do we find him?

24:03.833 --> 24:06.749
CAL: He could be anywhere.
He's a professional ghost.

24:19.588 --> 24:21.460
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

24:50.706 --> 24:52.578
[MILLS GRUNTS]

24:56.756 --> 24:57.844
[METALLIC RATTLING]

24:57.844 --> 24:59.019
What the hell's
going on back there?

25:01.108 --> 25:02.675
What the hell?

25:02.675 --> 25:06.113
Hey, Cargo, 1062. Over.

25:06.113 --> 25:11.118
MAN:Cargo, come in. Over.
Something's happening
in the back.

25:11.118 --> 25:14.338
Cargo, what's going on
there? Do we have a
situation back there?

25:14.338 --> 25:15.905
[GRUNTING]

25:15.905 --> 25:17.690
Cargo, come in. Over.

25:24.000 --> 25:26.176
[INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER]

25:31.834 --> 25:33.009
MAN: Cargo, what's
going down?

25:33.009 --> 25:35.055
All personnel, switch
to alternate frequencies.

25:35.055 --> 25:38.362
MAN:You guys okay?
What's going on?
What's going on?

25:40.495 --> 25:41.627
[GAS HISSING]

25:41.627 --> 25:42.671
[TIRES SCREECHING]

25:51.854 --> 25:53.639
[COUGHING]

26:01.081 --> 26:01.908
Go.

26:21.536 --> 26:23.277
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

26:23.277 --> 26:25.496
Fuck, fuck, fuck, fuck.

26:25.496 --> 26:26.759
[PANTING]

26:34.636 --> 26:37.421
REX: Don't move.
Eyes closed.

26:40.729 --> 26:42.383
Turn around.

26:52.480 --> 26:54.525
Gun, radio, drop them.

26:58.312 --> 27:01.271
